<div class="entry"><a title="See all Lesson Plans" href="/category/lesson-plans/"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/learning/learning_lesson-plan151.png" alt="Lesson Plans - The Learning Network" /></a><a title="See all lesson plans" href="/category/lesson-plans/"><img class="w35 right" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/learning/learning_lesson-plan35.png" alt="Lesson Plans - The Learning Network" /></a></p>
<h6 class="kicker">Global History</h6>
<p class="summary">Teaching ideas based on New York Times content.</p>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/category/global-history/">See all in Global History Â»</a></li>
<li><a title="See all Lesson Plans" href="/category/lesson-plans/">See all lesson plans Â»</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What happens when you ask 814 million people to decide the future of their country? The answer will be coming soon for India, which this week is concluding a huge, 35-day election for seats in the national Parliament. Observers say the results could be momentous, with polls suggesting that voters are fed up with slow economic or political progress and favor decisive change &#8212; even at the risk of upsetting the nationâs fragile balance between its religious and social groups.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In this lesson we explore the complex web of issues, history and culture behind the India vote. We begin with an overview of the political and organizational challenges of mounting an election in the subcontinent. Students can then explore more deeply, predict the electionâs outcome, track the results in The New York Times and look for clues on where the worldâs largest democracy is headed.<br />
<span id="more-145838"></span><br />
<strong>Warm-Up | </strong>For a quick introduction to the issues, students can watch this four-minute <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/world/asia/100000002805481/largest-democracy-who-will-lead-india.html">video</a> or this <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/world/asia/100000002825241/india-at-a-crossroads.html">more in-depth overview</a> (14 minutes) on the parties and issues in play during Indiaâs parliamentary elections and read these <a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/08/a-primer-on-indias-parliamentary-elections/">questions and answers</a> on the election process.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Then, working in small groups, students can use what they have learned to develop a short presentation on what they consider to be the most significant facts, issues and perspectives on the elections and democracy in India, as well as questions about things they want to learn more about. Students may design charts or drawings to illustrate their main points, drawing from both the article and video.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Students can also watch this BBC video, <a href="//www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-26878181">&#8220;Indian Elections: Everything You Need to Know in Two Minutes&#8221;</a> and discuss whether its title is accurate.</p>
<hr/>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/13/world/LADAKH-1-LN/LADAKH-1-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/13/world/LADAKH-1-LN/LADAKH-1-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/13/world/LADAKH-1-LN/LADAKH-1-blog480.jpg" id="100000002877570" width="480" height="331" alt="Election workers in the Leh District of India checked voting machines last week before leaving for polling stations. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/13/world/asia/hikers-spread-democracy-in-india.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="331"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Election workers in the Leh District of India checked voting machines last week before leaving for polling stations. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/13/world/asia/hikers-spread-democracy-in-india.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Kevin Frayer/Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Ways to Teach About the Indian Elections</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What is this yearâs Indian election really about? Students and teachers can explore the resources below in a variety of ways, for example, by making research-based predictions or simulating a mock campaign tour, in order to gain a deeper understanding. For further ideas on using this material, see the list at the bottom of this post.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>1. Counting to 814 Million.</strong><br />
How can you run an election in the worldâs second most populous country, from sprawling cities to far-flung rural villages, and get a reliable result? Read these stories and look for details on how Indiaâs election officials are managing the process, and how this vote differs from previous elections.</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/13/world/asia/hikers-spread-democracy-in-india.html">&#8220;Hikers Spread Democracy in India&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/10/setting-up-an-election-in-the-worlds-largest-democracy/">&#8220;Setting Up an Election in the Worldâs Largest Democracy&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/06/the-device-that-runs-the-worlds-biggest-election/">&#8220;The Device That Runs the Worldâs Biggest Election&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-26847432">&#8220;Indians Vote on Key Election Day&#8221;</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>2. Itâs All About the Voters.</strong><br />
Who are those 814 million eligible voters and what do they want? Watch the videos below and take notes on the perspectives of individual voters and citizens, as well as the politicians who are trying to capture their votes. Then develop a list or chart of âtypical voters,â their concerns and their voting tendencies or sympathies.</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/world/asia/100000002825241/india-at-a-crossroads.html?playlistId=100000002776751">&#8220;India at a Crossroads&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/multimedia/100000002748053/india-election-polls-provide-more-confusion-than-clarity.html">&#8220;India Election Polls Provide More Confusion Than Clarity&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/world/asia/100000000828070/india-rising-off-the-grid-.html">&#8220;India Rising, Off the Grid&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/world/asia/100000002829147/new-delhi-votes.html?playlistId=100000002776751">&#8220;New Delhi Votes&#8221;</a></li>
</ul>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/08/world/INDIA-LN/INDIA-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/08/world/INDIA-LN/INDIA-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/08/world/INDIA-LN/INDIA-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002877576" width="190" height="127" alt="A voting station in Majuli, in the northeastern state of Assam. Indians began voting for members of Parliament on April 7. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/08/world/asia/wish-for-change-animates-voters-in-india-election.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="127"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A voting station in Majuli, in the northeastern state of Assam. Indians began voting for members of Parliament on April 7. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/08/world/asia/wish-for-change-animates-voters-in-india-election.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Adnan Abidi/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>3. Itâs All About Modi</strong><br />
Polls suggest that one candidate, Narendra Modi, stands the best chance of winding up on top. As chief minister of the Gujarat state and leader of the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), he has presided over spectacular economic growth and challenged a culture of corruption in government. But he was also on duty when more than a thousand people were killed in Hindu-Muslim riots in 2002; many say he should have done more to end the violence, and hasnât done enough since to reduce ethnic tensions. Examine the following resources and then decide: Who is the real Modi, and is he the right candidate to lead all of India?</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/13/world/asia/hikers-spread-democracy-in-india.html">&#8220;Hikers Spread Democracy in India&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/08/world/asia/wish-for-change-animates-voters-in-india-election.html">&#8220;Wish for Change Animates Voters in India Election&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-27249952">&#8220;The Making of Narendra Modi&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/world/asia/100000002805547/narendra-modis-past.html">&#8220;Indiaâs Next Prime Minister?&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/04/06/world/asia/modi-gujarat-riots-timeline.html">&#8220;Timeline of the Riots in Modiâs Gujarat&#8221;</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>4. Itâs All About Gandhi</strong><br />
Ever since Indiaâs independence from Britain in 1947, the country has been dominated by a single family and its political party. But their grip on power may be loosening as voters grow restless waiting for improvements to the economy, government and services. Can Rahul Gandhi and the Indian National Congress provide the change &#8212; along with their traditional focus on promoting equality for people of all religious, ethnic and social backgrounds &#8212; that voters demand?</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/10/world/asia/in-india-support-cools-for-a-gandhi-in-a-traditional-stronghold.html">&#8220;In Stronghold, a Gandhi Finds the Reception Is More Skeptical than Worshipful&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/01/world/asia/political-stumbling-leaves-an-indian-heir-less-apparent.html">&#8220;An Uneasy Inheritance of Indiaâs Political Dynasty&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/world/asia/100000002805481/largest-democracy-who-will-lead-india.html">&#8220;A Vote Against Congress in India?&#8221;</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>5. Other Candidates, Other Parties</strong><br />
Because India is a parliamentary democracy, itâs possible that no single political party will gain enough seats to win outright control of the government. If thatâs the case, it will need partners from other groups to form a coalition. Who are the most significant figures besides Narendra Modi and Rahul Gandhi, and how can a small party or a single candidate influence a national election or government? Assign students or groups to profile lesser-known candidates or parties, and suggest whether they are likely to have a significant impact on the electionâs outcome.</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/03/world/asia/an-unlikely-indian-political-stars-latest-crusade.html">&#8220;An Unlikely Indian Political Starâs Latest Crusade&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/17/world/asia/female-candidate-navigates-hurdle-filled-campaign-trail-in-india.html">&#8220;Political Novice in India Meets a Gritty Reality on the Campaign Trail&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/13/world/asia/coalition-building-season-in-india.html">&#8220;Coalition-Building Season in India&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.aljazeera.com/indepth/interactive/2014/04/india-political-parties-their-symbols-201446115541946199.html">&#8220;India&#8217;s Political Parties and Their Symbols&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/11/world/asia/in-indian-candidate-hindu-right-sees-a-reawakening.html">&#8220;In Indian Candidate, Hindu Right Sees a Reawakening&#8221;</a></li>
</ul>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/08/13/arts/video-partition-LN/video-partition-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/08/13/arts/video-partition-LN/video-partition-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/08/13/arts/video-partition-LN/video-partition-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002877597" width="190" height="125" alt="The 1947 Partition Archive is gathering oral histories of those who lived through the violent split of India and Pakistan. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2013/08/14/arts/potent-memories-from-a-divided-india.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="125"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">The 1947 Partition Archive is gathering oral histories of those who lived through the violent split of India and Pakistan. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/08/14/arts/potent-memories-from-a-divided-india.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>6. Voting on History</strong><br />
From its bloody division into two nations at independence in 1947 to the continuing influence of a founding father, Mohandas K. Gandhi, the weight of history is felt by many people every day across India. On the other hand, almost half of India&#8217;s voters are<a href="//www.theindianrepublic.com/tbp/will-youth-vote-influence-2014-general-polls-100028102.html"> under the age of 35</a> and have grown up with the expectation of living in a modern, digital economy. Do you think the memory of past events will affect the choices of voters, or are present-day concerns more relevant? Read the stories below, using a map of South Asia to find place names as theyâre mentioned.  (You might also wish to find a <a href="https://www.google.com/search?q=india+map+muslim+percentage&#038;source=lnms&#038;tbm=isch&#038;sa">map</a> showing the percentage of Hindus and Muslims in different parts of the country.) Then suggest ways in which history might or might not play a part in the outcome of the elections.</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/08/14/arts/potent-memories-from-a-divided-india.html">&#8220;Potent Memories From a Divided India&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2010/11/07/world/asia/07gandhi.html">&#8220;Obama Invokes Gandhi, Whose Ideal Eludes India&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/03/20/opinion/revisiting-gandhi-on-the-banks-of-the-sabarmati.html">&#8220;Revisiting Gandhi, on the Banks of the Sabarmati&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/world/asia/IndiasWay.html">&#8220;Indiaâs Way&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/11/15/in-bangladesh-stranded-on-the-borders-of-two-bengals/">&#8220;In Bangladesh, Stranded on the Borders of Two Bengals&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/11/15/in-india-cross-border-bengali-pride-fades-with-a-new-generation/">&#8220;In India, Cross-Border Bengali Pride Fades With a New Generation&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/10/19/world/asia/killings-thwart-grass-roots-democracy-in-india.html">&#8220;Killings Derail Effort at Grass-Roots Governance in India&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/30/with-election-many-reminded-of-horrors-of-2002-gujarat-riots/">&#8220;With Election, Many Reminded of Horrors of 2002 Gujarat Riots&#8221;</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>7. Gender Matters</strong><br />
It has been only two years since a brutal gang rape in Delhi prompted a national debate about womenâs rights and violence prevention. But has anything changed? Read about the original case below, subsequent attacks and the ways in which gender issues have been handled during the election campaign. Then formulate a proposal on how Indian women could make further improvements and perhaps shift the agenda using digital technology and social media.</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/12/29/world/asia/condition-worsens-for-victim-of-gang-rape-in-india.html">&#8220;Woman Dies After a Gang Rape That Galvanized India&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/23/what-female-voters-say-about-womens-safety-in-mumbai/">&#8220;What Female Voters Say About Womenâs Safety in Mumbai&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/world/asia/100000002870883/the-politics-of-violence-against-women.html">&#8220;A Vote Against Violence for Indian Women&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/09/rhetoric-about-womens-issues-outpaces-political-progress/">&#8220;Rhetoric About Womenâs Issues Outpaces Political Progress&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/11/opinion/sunday/kristof-whats-so-scary-about-smart-girls.html">&#8220;Whatâs So Scary About Smart Girls?&#8221;</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>8. Caste Matters</strong><br />
Caste divisions are alive and well across India, despite a decades-long effort to stamp out the discrimination and conflict that have resulted from these historical social groupings. Are the issues the same as during Mohandas Gandhiâs time, when the focus was on stamping out the tradition of excluding some groups as âuntouchable?&#8221; Or have castes evolved for modern times? Consider the ways in which caste has affected the elections and voting, as well as the potential for economic development to ease its influence.</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/17/in-bihar-economic-concerns-are-tied-up-in-caste-politics/">&#8220;In Bihar, Economic Concerns Are Tied Up in Caste Politics&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/02/opinion/roy-testing-the-ideas-of-india.html">&#8220;Testing the Ideas of India&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.economist.com/blogs/economist-explains/2014/02/economist-explains-9">&#8220;Why Caste Still Matters in India&#8221;</a></li>
</ul>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/16/world/asia/16-bangalore-indiaink-LN/16-bangalore-indiaink-articleInline-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/16/world/asia/16-bangalore-indiaink-LN/16-bangalore-indiaink-articleInline-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/16/world/asia/16-bangalore-indiaink-LN/16-bangalore-indiaink-articleInline-v2.jpg" id="100000002877650" width="190" height="122" alt="Publicity material of Narendra Modi, the Bharatiya Janata Party&#039;s candidate for prime minister, on sale in Bangalore. &lt;a href=&quot;//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/16/candidates-exploit-loopholes-to-skirt-spending-limits/&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="122"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Publicity material of Narendra Modi, the Bharatiya Janata Party's candidate for prime minister, on sale in Bangalore. <a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/16/candidates-exploit-loopholes-to-skirt-spending-limits/">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Jagadeesh Nv/European Pressphoto Agency</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>9. Follow the Money</strong><br />
Many say corruption is a fact of life in Indian politics, with several parties campaigning against the influence of money  in voting and government. But thatâs easier said than done, as long as political candidates continue trying to purchase votes with gifts of money or alcohol, and government officials accept or demand payment for services. Read the stories below. Then consider new, grass-roots efforts to expose corruption through the websites like <a href="//www.ipaidabribe.com/">I Paid a Bribe.</a> What do you think is the best approach to ending corruption and reducing the influence of money in Indiaâs government?</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/10/opinion/indias-price-of-victory.html">&#8220;Votes for Crooks and Cricket Stars&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/16/candidates-exploit-loopholes-to-skirt-spending-limits/">&#8220;Candidates Exploit Loopholes to Skirt Spending Limits&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/09/10/world/asia/as-corruption-abates-hope-amid-a-slowdown.html">&#8220;As Corruption Abates, Hope Amid a Slowdown&#8221;</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>10. Learning from Indiaâs Example</strong><br />
Does democracy work effectively in India compared with other places, and what can be done to improve it? Consider these stories about democracy in other parts of South Asia, and the compromises that have been made to keep elective politics going in India, as well as the changes that were made in 2014 to make the process more fair or effective.  Based on everything you have read, what grade would you give the 2014 Indian parliamentary elections, from A to F? Please make sure to explain your grade.</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/14/lessons-for-the-largest-democracy-from-a-much-smaller-one/">&#8220;Lessons for the Largest Democracy From a Much Smaller One&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2009/05/03/opinion/03fernandes.html">&#8220;Selling Democracy (and Tea) in India&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/11/28/world/asia/voters-in-maldives-join-in-regions-halting-steps-toward-democracy.html">&#8220;A Region Totters Toward Democracy, Gathering Momentum&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-26847432">&#8220;Indians Vote on Key Election Day&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/may/10/indian-elections-narendra-modi-bjp-western-policy">&#8220;The Indian Election and the Lessons the West Can Take From Narendra Modi&#8217;s Popularity&#8221;</a></li>
</ul>
