    data-videoid="100000002870883" data-media-action="modal" data-autoplay="" data-embedded="true" aria-label="media" role="group">
        <span class="visually-hidden">Video</span>

    <figcaption class="caption">
        <h4 class="headline">A Vote Against Violence for Indian Women</h4>
		        <div class="caption-video">
                <div class="summary-credit">
            <p class="summary">After a brutal gang rape in New Delhi, something changed in India. But maybe not a lot for the countryâs politicians. For Nasreen Jahan, the fight for justice in this election season is personal.</p>
            <span class="credit video-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
                By Poh Si Teng and Malavika Vyawahare on                                                    <span class="visually-hidden">Publish Date </span>May 8, 2014.
                            </span>
            <span class="credit photo-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
                            </span>
        </div>

                    <div class="sharetools-video-container">
                <div id="sharetools-video-tools-100000002870883"
                    class="sharetools sharetools-video-tools">
                    <ul>
                        <li class="sharetool embed-sharetool">
                            <a href="javascript:;" data-share="embed" data-modal-title="">
                                <i class="icon sprite-icon"></i>
                                <span class="sharetool-text ">embed</span>
                            </a>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div id="sharetools-video-inline-100000002870883"
                    class="sharetools sharetools-video-inline"
                    data-shares="facebook|,twitter|"
                    data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/video/world/asia/100000002870883/the-politics-of-violence-against-women.html?action=click&amp;contentCollection=world&amp;module=blog-video&amp;region=caption&amp;pgtype=article"
                    data-title="A Vote Against Violence for Indian Women"
                    data-description="After a brutal gang rape in New Delhi, something changed in India. But maybe not a lot for the countryâs politicians. For Nasreen Jahan, the fight for justice in this election season is personal."
                    data-content-type="video">
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
            </figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Going Further | </strong>Classes can adopt many strategies to dig deeper on issues related to democracy in India. For example:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">1. Assign students to read key stories in order to make an informed, research-based prediction on the electionâs outcome. They should write up their predictions and back up their claims with evidence. Then <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/international/countriesandterritories/india/index.html">track the results</a> at weekâs end and consider which predictions came closest.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">2. Allow students to pose their own questions about the election, or to choose one from the list below, and then conduct research using the stories above.  You may want students to write a detailed analytical paper or to create an informational poster or digital presentation. As part of the process, you may also choose to hold a structured class discussion or a teach-in on the elections and invite other classes to attend.  Possible in-depth research questions include:</p>
<ul>
<li>What is the defining quality or characteristic of Indiaâs 2014 parliamentary elections?</li>
<li>What should be the democratic vision for India?</li>
<li>Should India be a secular democracy or a Hindu-dominated state?</li>
<li>Is a certain level of authoritarianism necessary to promote development and fight poverty, or will such policies lead to ethnic strife and political gridlock?</li>
<li>Does the election process seem to be a unifying or dividing force in India, and how might the election results help to answer that question?</li>
<li>How do politics really work in India? Consider the behavior of voters, regional power brokers, political parties and coalitions.</li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">3. Design a mock campaign tour across India in which students adopt the roles of voters, candidates and journalists. All three groups research the issues at stake as well as the major candidates&#8217; positions. Then, the class holds a series of campaign events where the candidates deliver speeches, the journalists ask pointed questions and the voters write reflections explaining whom they would vote for and why. </p>
<hr/>
